In .NET MAUI, use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in your `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;

public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

    builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
    {
#if ANDROID
        events.AddAndroid(android => android
            .OnPause(activity =>
            {
                // Runs when the activity is pausing
            })
            .OnStop(activity =>
            {
                // Runs when the activity is no longer visible
            }));
#endif

#if IOS
        events.AddiOS(ios => ios
            .DidEnterBackground(application =>
            {
                // Runs when the app enters the background
            }));
#endif
    });

    return builder.Build();
}
```

**Key points:**

- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;`
- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code separated
- The delegates give you the native object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS) so you can call platform APIs directly
- Other available Android events: `OnCreate`, `OnResume`, `OnDestroy`, `OnRestart`
- Other available iOS events: `WillEnterForeground`, `WillTerminate`, `OnActivated`, `OnResignActivation`
